Turkey expands its diplomatic horizons
Long before Turkey became a member of the European Union, the European powers were nesting the desire to penetrate the interior of this country.
In the eastern part of the Bosphorus, perhaps only 20 steps into Asia, is one of the most interesting relics of the disastrous imperial ambition.
The Hydarpasha train station was designed by two German architects, Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu, in a neo-Renaissance style.
At least that’s what the guides say.
The building is set to end the platforms and carries in front of two towers, one for each corner, all looking like a typical German city hall.
The stone is dirty.
The building in its complex is a bit decadent.
But once the vaulted box office was over, there is no doubt what was the grandeur of the company that this was the westernmost gate.
The station was inaugurated in August 1908 by the German consortium Anatolia-Bagdad Corporation.
Germany, a "late-eater" in the imperial game, had the ambition to dominate the Middle East through this railway that ran to Damascus, Baghdad, and beyond in what is now Saudi Arabia.
However, the ambitions of this imperial Germany failed during World War I.
Its railways were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and its irregular Arabs.
Because of the relative isolation of the surrounding regions, generated by the frozen borders of the Cold War, it fell below the borders of the United States.
British rule and as forces advanced into Egypt, they pushed the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
The news was also bad for the Hyderpasha station.
In 1917 a train of ammunition exploded destroying its elaborate roof.
Turkish sources said it was sabotage.
Since then the station has been decaying and left out of the story.
But today, this railway, the gateway to Anatolia and all the eastern centres, serves - at least symbolically - to highlight Turkey's willingness to broaden its diplomatic horizons.
The Justice and Development Party that is in government - the AKP - has planned a new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation of the surrounding regions, generated by the frozen borders of the Cold War, has disappeared.
There is now a new collaboration policy.
The Turkish government maintains excellent relations with Israel and Syria, with both the Palestinian factions of Hamas and Fatah, with Iraq and Iran and, of course, with the European Union and the United States.
To assess the parameters of this new foreign policy, I got on a bunk bed and went to the Turkish capital Ankara, in order to visit one of the leaders of the AKP, an expert on foreign policy, the Turkish Prime Minister Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning - about ten and a half hours later - after a trip of jolts, which produced the cadences of the ancient world in the famous documentary The Night Mail, I arrived in the Turkish capital - new city, meant to rule a new secular state, away from the Ottoman past.
However, the AKP, with its clear Islamist roots, represents a paradigmatic shift in the Turkish consensus.
It has raised some suspicions in the West and especially in Washington.
A taxi takes me to the headquarters of the AKP, an ultra-modern stone and steel structure - built ad hoc - in a developing suburb, surrounded by half-built shopping malls and "power pastries" where middle-class managers in business suit - men and women - meet early in the morning to agree/do business.
Suat Kiniklioglu could be a center-right politician of almost any party in Europe.
I'm sure he still has a Blackberry.
“The goal of the party’s foreign policy is to reintegrate Turkey into its immediate neighbourhood.
The Cold War was an anomaly,” he tells me.
Turkey has been cut off in relations with its interior.
Today you have to look at the East and the West at the same time.
This is not a case if it is not for one or the other.
You have to do both.
"But surely at some point," I ask, "could Turkey be forced to choose?"
"Turkey," he replies, "does not want to face that choice."
He then underlines a point that almost everyone I have spoken to so far had almost recited to me in memory: Turkey's relations not only with the Middle East, but with the Caucasus region, and with the whole of the Black Sea, represent a benefit for Europe and the United States, as well as for Turkey itself.
The message seems to be: With Turkey on board, Europe in its complex can metaphorically assemble those railway lines that open the world to East Asia and the Middle East.
Once again to the station of Hydarpasha, after a second sleepless night, my thought goes back to the two German lords, Herr Ritter and Herr Conu, who had attended the construction of this building, 100 years ago.
How surprised would they have been to know that Europe’s ambitions in the Middle East, in large part, would be in the hands of Turkey today?
And waiting at the terminal for the ferry that will take me back across the Bosphorus, I remember that in those days Turkey was considered "the sick man of Europe."
So, there is not much doubt in which continent this fascinating country must claim.
