Morgan Stanley lost 6.79% at $23.07 each at 17:00 GMT.
“This strategic alliance represents an important opportunity to accelerate Morgan Stanley’s transition to bank holding status,” said Juan Mack, CEO of the American Group.
Morgan Stanley adopted this new statute last week, which would have to allow him to diversify his activities but he passes under the authority of the Federal Reserve.
His alliance with MUFG also confirms that the current financial crisis forces the biggest names on Wall Street to adopt a much more prudent behavior than before.
The modalities presented last Monday also show that the deal has been modified over the past few days: Last Monday, Morgan had announced that it would sell up to 20% of its shares to Japan for nearly $8.5 billion.
“A week ago,” explained Toshihide Mizuno, the executive director of MUFG, “we thought the stake would have been made up of only ordinary shares.
But in view of the current economic and market situation, we have wanted to minimize the risks and cover ourselves.”
Based on the weighted average price, MUFG will pay its Morgan Stanley securities 7% below its accounting value.
And the transaction will result in a dilution of about 20% of the profit per share.
The agreement provides that MUFG will be able to convert half of its preferred securities into ordinary shares within a year if they are sold at more than 50% above the conversion price, or at $47 or so, over a given period.
Morgan Stanley says the capital provided by MUFG will allow it to capture investment opportunities, strengthen its balance sheet and increase its liquidity.
A spokeswoman for the group refused, however, to clarify the strategic projects of the two new allies.
After MUFG’s investment, Morgan Stanley should show a Tier One solvency ratio of about 15%, one of the best in the industry.
Morgan said he had greatly eased his balance sheet since the end of August.
The last few weeks have been exhausting for the group, which saw its stock price fall in half as the cost of security against a risk of defects on its debt took off.
This cost fell back on Monday but remained at a high level, around 12%.
Last week, Goldman Sachs, the only other "survivor" of the major Wall Street investment banks after the bankruptcies of Bear Stearns and Lehman Brothers and the purchase of Merrill Lynch, announced it had raised $15 billion, partly for Berkshire Hathaway, Warren Buffett's group.
Rafael Correa in Quito, this Monday.
Refounding the republic around 21st century socialism.
This is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
This Sunday, like his colleagues and friends, he is the third to put to the vote a draft for a new constitution.
Mission accomplished since 64% of voters voted "yes" to the referendum, according to official results that referred to 80% of the votes.
According to these results, the "no" obtained 28%, 7% of the votes were voting null and 0.7% were blank votes.
In order for the draft constitution to be adopted, half of the votes plus one had to be obtained.
On Sunday, two polls conducted outside the polling stations and a count by a non-governmental organization had announced a broad victory for the "yes", estimating it between 63% and 70%.
Rafael Correa had also claimed on the night of Sunday to Monday the victory of his draft constitution.
The “Constitution triumphed overwhelmingly,” he said, congratulating the Ecuadorians who head the government of Guayaquil, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
Thus, Rafael Correa has been congratulated by Chávez and Morales but also by his Chilean colleague Micaela Bachelet.
The elections, which will take place in full calm, according to the Organization of American States (OAS) observation mission, referred to a 444-point text that consolidated the " new socialism " defended by the president.
The draft Constitution implies increasing the power of the State over the economy, reserving it for the " development planning " of a country that lives essentially thanks to the extraction of oil by foreign companies and thanks to foreign exchange that sends its emigrants.
Led by Correa, elected in 2006, the project also grants reinforced powers to the head of state, who can hold up to two consecutive terms of four years each and will have the possibility of dissolving the Assembly.
Correa has already announced that he would use this power and intend a new term in February 2009.
The Constitution also consolidates the principle of free health and education services that the president began to establish in this country of 13.9 million inhabitants, in which 50% of the population lives under the poverty line.
It finally foresees a ban on the presence of foreign troops, which will end the agreement between Quito and Washington for the use of an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for American anti-drug operations.
All 19 abductees have been released in Chad
An Egyptian commando launched the assault on the kidnappers of the eleven tourists and their eight companions captured ten days ago.
They're in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian escorts kidnapped ten days ago in the desert arrived unharmed in the Egyptian capital after being released on Monday afternoon.
In the morning, they had been liberated by Egyptian special forces in Chad.
All of them looked good on their arrival at 3.30 p.m. aboard a special aircraft to the Al Maza military base, adjacent to Cairo International Airport.
Helicopters immediately transported them to Maadi hospital, a residential suburb of Cairo, for medical testing, so they were unable to speak to the press.
"They are in good health" and "no ransom was paid" to the kidnappers, Egyptian Tourism Minister Zoheir Garana said at the airport.
On September 19, these hostages fell into the hands of 35 unknown hijackers while enjoying an off-road safari in a desert area at the foot of Mount Ouanat, in the confines of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, and since then they have passed from one zoo to another.
The group consisted of eleven tourists - five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian - and eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of the travel agency Aegyptous, in charge of the organization of the safari.
An Egyptian security official said 30 special forces members, carried aboard two helicopters, had launched the assault overnight before dawn.
"An exchange of shots occurred, and half of the kidnappers were killed, the others have fled," said the official who kept the anonymous.
According to him, 150 members of the Egyptian special forces of the "lightning" unit were sent to Sudan, where they were supported by German and Italian commandos.
The Italian Foreign Minister, Franco Frattini, mentioned in Belgrade the role played by secret agents and members of the Italian special forces.
"We must recognize that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and effectiveness of our men of the secret services, of the special forces," he said without going into details.
He also denied the payment of a ransom.
The day before, the Sudanese army claimed to have intercepted during a patrol an off-roader on board which were the kidnappers, of whom six were killed, including the Chadian chief and arrested two.
He also claimed that they were related to a rebel group in Darfur, the Sudan-Unity Liberation Movement (SLA-U), an assertion immediately denied by that group.
