The governments of the Netherlands nationalize a part of the Fortis Bank.
The states of the Netherlands - being the first in Europe - will help with a nationalization to the Belgian-Dutch bank Fortis that is in trouble due to the effect of the mortgage crisis of the North American market: the three countries will support in total with 11.2 billion euros to this financial and insurance institution that also has businesses in Hungary.
This weekend the governments of Belgium, Luxembourg and the Netherlands held consultations at the highest level with the president of the European Central Bank and the head of economic competition of the European Commission.
The Fortis Bank is the first to suffer from the Eurozone crisis in the context of the international financial crisis that has been occurring in several waves more than a year ago, so the decisions taken with regard to the Bank, in a sense, can be considered precedents.
According to the decision taken early on Sunday, the three states will buy about half (49 percent) of the Bank’s property in their area.
The Bank will certainly sell a portion of its business, among them mainly the activities - mainly insurance - bought last year from Dutch ABN Amró.
Fortis stocks started a sharp decline last week and by the second half of the week there were already significant signs of crisis in the institution.
However, analysts agree that with its 85,000 employees, this bank is too large to allow it to go bankrupt.
The company's shares fell 12 percent on Friday alone, the lowest point in the last 14 years.
Since January, the value of the shares has declined by more than two-thirds.
Looking at current stock prices, the total value of the group’s capital in the market is around 14 billion euros, but according to the company’s executives this is not real.
The Bank’s management blamed the sharp drop in Fortis shares on the insecurity of the US market in connection with the approval of the US $700 billion package plan.
On Monday, stocks showed a slight increase.
On Friday, they appointed Filip Dierckx as the bank’s new CEO.
The Bank also sought private investors, but so far no one has given a concrete offer.
The Belgian government had previously assured investors that they would not have to worry, they would not lose their money.
Among the Bank’s clients so far there was no panic, they did not invade the banking offices to withdraw their money.
Fortis has its own branch in Hungary and has also purchased leasing companies.
Fox in the chicken coop
In the United States, health and life insurance companies often refuse to sign an insurance contract when viewing drug purchase data.
Privacy policy specialists fear that the personal data market will become uncontrollable.
"There are programs for the protection of personal data, which the use of prescription data in all cases unites it with the approval of the given person.
He must be in independent hands, because otherwise, “we trust the chicken coop to the fox” – quotes the Washington Post from Richard Dick, the designer of the prescription tracking program.
Insurance companies make the insurance price and the amount of compensation dependent on the client’s health status and if they believe the risk is excessive, they simply do not make the contract.
Before they sent the client to medical check and signed the contract with him knowing the result of the check.
Dick invented a much cheaper procedure ten years ago: with the customer identification number he easily gets from pharmacies the list of drugs purchased in the last year and a half and the program itself draws the conclusion about the diseases and health status of the customer.
For example, if you consistently take large doses of cholesterol-lowering pills, it indicates that your blood fat level is virtually incurably high, so you are immediately included in a higher risk category.
Numerous versions of the program circulate, some even establish a risk number, so the insurance company in addition to the administration has hardly anything to do, although there are small difficulties in it.
Among the disadvantages of the program is for example that some drugs are multi-purpose, for example certain substances serve both to treat headaches and heat waves and even as antidepressants.
The latter is a major risk-increasing factor for insurance companies while the former do not.
Special companies were set up to consult and process these data, which before acquiring the necessary information from the pharmacies, ask for the patient's approval.
The authorities are already obliging them to do this, although they have not received a fine for the negligence so far.
Some companies have also been developing laboratory test results and combining them with drug consumption data to gain more accurate information about the patient’s health status.
More and more companies have access to this data and at the same time it is increasingly difficult to control its use.
There is an exclusive law for the protection of personal health data, but it applies only to insurance companies and those that provide health services.
The bill that gives the right to the authority to control specialized companies for the provision of personal data is already before Congress.
Dick Richard acknowledges that this is insufficient: he therefore developed his program, which will require the specific approval of the person for the provision of his own personal data.
It is another issue that such a person cannot deny his approval, because otherwise the insurance companies will not sign the contract with him.
So that the hens, in spite of everything, are exposed to the goodwill of the fox.
