The European Union doubles its trade with India
As the European Union and India are mutual trade partners, this issue, in addition to the other mostly global issues, dominated the agenda of the ninth summit.
A Franco-Indian summit will also be held today, mainly to discuss cooperation in nuclear energy.
Although the European Union recognizes that India is a major developing democratic power that should have more voice and vote in international affairs, the member countries have yet to reach a common denominator on whether they should support New Delhi as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
This issue has not been dealt with at the ninth summit started yesterday in Marseille.
French President Nicolas Sarkozy, EU President-in-Chair, Commission President José Manuel Barroso and Javier Solana, the main representative of foreign policy, welcomed Manmohan Singh, Prime Minister of India with whom they reached an agreement to double in five years, that is to increase to more than one hundred billion euros, their trade exchange.
Bearing in mind that between 2000 and 2007 the exchange of goods increased from 25 billion to 55 billion, this is not an overly ambitious objective.
Thus they legally harmonised the twenty-six existing bilateral civil aviation agreements with India, so that air transport can also fly in the future.
India wants to sign a free trade agreement with the Union by the end of 2009.
Sarkozy promised to speed up the negotiations.
The goal is balance, because while the EU is India’s first trading partner, New Delhi is only ranked ninth among the Union’s trading partners.
The summit paid its attention to global issues.
Both sides condemned the Afghan and Pakistani situation and terrorism – all forms of the latter – and urged the convening of a UN conference.
The conclusion of the Doha trade liberalization round was also urged, although both sides bear great responsibility for its failure.
The EU has confirmed that it will stick to its energy and climate programme, i.e. by 2020 it wants to reduce polluting emissions by at least 20 percent.
India also agrees with this, as at next year’s climate conference a global agreement should be reached and production of greenhouse gases should be reduced by fifty percent by 2050.
They also wish to impede rising food prices and supported the convening of an international conference to review the financial crisis.
Today the head of government of India will travel to the French capital, where - at a bilateral meeting - will sign an agreement on the peaceful use of nuclear energy.
Paris is confident that French companies will receive orders worth 20 billion euros to build nuclear reactors.
According to news agency reports, the agreement would be for a period of 15 years.
